c Databases data floodhazard html Data Flood Hazard Mapping data landslide html Data Landslide Hazard Mapping data aerial html Data Aerial Photography Satellite Imagery data streamgage html Data Stream Gage Networks country elsalvador html El Salvador country guatemala html Guatemala country honduras html Honduras country nicaragua html Nicaragua publications factsheets html Fact Sheets publications powerpoint html Presentations publications reports html Reports acronym html Acronyms resources html Links GIS Products Project Chief Paul Hearn Phone 703 648 6287 Email phearn usgs gov Project Summary GIS map GIS technology offers powerful tools to compile and analyze information needed by municipal and national agencies for disaster mitigation preparedness and response GIS is not widely used in Central America however due to the lack of digital maps baseline data data on hazards lack of GIS hardware software and basic knowledge of GIS principles Objectives In coordination with USAID Missions counterpart agencies and municipal officials the project will develop 1 50 000 scale GIS s for approximately 70 priority municipal areas in Honduras 40 sites Nicaragua 16 sites El Salvador 7 sites and Guatemala 7 sites These GIS s will integrate digital base maps aerial photography maps of flood and landslide risk and other information needed for disaster mitigation and response GIS s will be delivered as ArcView and ArcExplorer projects on CD ROM and also as paper maps The project will develop Disaster Management GIS s with counterpart agencies in Honduras Nicaragua El Salvador and Guatemala at medium map scale 1 250 000 for use as a planning tool by National Civil Defense agencies The project will work with counterpart agencies in Central America and NOAA to develop integrated GIS databases to support physical and biological assessments of shrimp breeding areas in the Gulf of Fonseca and coral reefs and nearshore ecosystems in the vicinity of the Bay Islands The project will conduct workshops to enure that sufficient in country expertise with GIS exists so that municipalities and National Civil Defense agencies can use and continue to build the GIS products provided to them Approach The USGS is already working with USAID Missions in Central America to facilitate the availability of digital and paper maps acquire post Mitch Aerial and Satellite Imagery create maps of areas at risk from future flooding and landslides and to provide hardware software and training to build local capacity in GIS The GIS project will build upon these ongoing activites by developing simple low cost GIS products to assist priority municipalities in disaster mitigation response and planning national disaster management GIS s for use by Civil Defense Agencies in each country municipal disaster GIS s for use by municipalities and local or regional institutions GIS products to integrate biological assessments in the Gulf of Fonseca and Bay Islands The project will also organize workshops and training to enhance the ability of specialists from municipalities and counterpart agencies to acquire and analyze simple geospatial data The project will work with national counterpart agencies and selected priority municipalities in Honduras Nicaragua Guatemala and El Salvador Contacts will be with counterpart staff in federal agencies USAID designated NGO s and also with engineers and other municipal officials in priority municipalities Cooperating Agencies Honduras UNITEC IGN COPECO SERNA FUNDEMUN Nicaragua INETER Civil Defense Committee MAGFOR El Salvador IGN COEN Guatemala IGN CONRED Universidad del Valle Source Data Local organization in the four countries the EROS Data Center the National Mapping Division and the Eastern Earth Surface Processes Team of the Geologic Division in Reston VA Products GIS data and custom applications The Municipal GIS is based on the compilation of several layers of information for an area of at least ten kilometers by ten kilometers around the t